Beebe","middle_name":"Hooker","last_name":"Strong","married_names":[],"gender":"male","display_name":"Beebe Hooker Strong","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1778958093/beebestrong_yqiosu.jpg","photo_notes":"Beebe Hooker Strong (1866-1933), prominent Baraboo Wisconsin businessman and local historian"},"birth":{"year":1866,"month":6,"day":19,"city":"Wauwatosa","county":"Milwaukee County","state":"Wisconsin","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1933,"country":"United States"},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM440","plot_notes":"Forest Home Cemetery Milwaukee per FA"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"generation_from_john_talcott":7,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"H02018","mother_id":"I00916"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00929","location_country":"United States","children_ids":["HD4648","HD4649"]}],"education":[],"career":[{"role":"Treasurer","organization":"Baraboo Gas & Electric Light Company, Baraboo, Wisconsin","notes":"W.H. Hopkins was president; B.H. Strong treasurer per period records."},{"role":"Local historian and civic leader","organization":"Baraboo, Wisconsin","end_year":1933,"notes":"Compiled and preserved historical accounts of the Baraboo region; documented account of how the Baraboo River received its name. Also managed local real estate."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[{"name_element":"Hooker","inspired_by_id":"H00001","description":"Middle name 'Hooker' honors the maternal Hooker ancestry — his mother was Rosa Searls Warner Strong, wife of Robert Hunter Strong, whose mother Dolly Goodwin Hooker carried the Hooker surname directly."},{"name_element":"Beebe","inspired_by_id":"I00900","description":"First name 'Beebe' honors the Beebe family — his great-grandfather Judge Elisha BEEBE Strong (I00900) took the Beebe surname from his mother Mary Beebe Strong of Windsor, CT."}],"artworks":[],"tags":["named_for_hooker","newspaper"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"H00673","display_label":"Both bore the Hooker name through the Strong family, 90 years apart","link_text":"Asahel Hooker Strong"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"The name 'Hooker' traveled from Farmington to Milwaukee","body":"Beebe Hooker Strong was born in Milwaukee in June 1866, bearing a middle name that traces a 137-year arc: his great-great-grandmother Sarah Hooker of Farmington, Connecticut had married into the Strong family in 1729, her great-great-grandson Asahel Hooker Strong preserved the name in Connecticut in 1776, and his grandmother Dolly Goodwin Hooker married a Strong again in 1813. The 'Hooker' in his name was a deliberate act of genealogical memory — a Wisconsin family's way of honoring the Hartford Puritan founder in whose blood they knew themselves to share."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Preserved how the Baraboo River got its name","body":"Beebe Hooker Strong became a prominent civic figure in Baraboo, Wisconsin — Treasurer of the Baraboo Gas & Electric Light Company — where he compiled and preserved the documented account explaining how the Baraboo River received its unusual name, a piece of regional oral history that would otherwise have passed unrecorded. The same instinct that drove him to document local origins animated his family's naming practice: they called him 'Hooker' so that no descendant would forget where they came from, and he spent his career ensuring Baraboo didn't forget where it came from either."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"Edward Hooker, Descendants of Rev. Thomas Hooker (1909)","url":"https://archive.org/details/descendantsofrev00hook"},{"label":"History of Descendants of Elder John Strong, Vol. 1 (1871)","url":"https://dn720908.ca.archive.org/0/items/historyofdescend0001dwig/historyofdescend0001dwig.pdf"},{"label":"FindAGrave","url":"https://www.findagrave.com"},{"label":"Wisconsin Historical Society — Newspaper Records BA5205","url":"https://www.wisconsinhistory.org/Records/Newspaper/BA5205"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"beebe-strong-1866"},"I00929":{"id":"I00929","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Mary","middle_name":"Louise","last_name":"Strong","maiden_name":"Caldwell","married_names":["Strong"],"gender":"female","display_name":"Mary Louise Caldwell Strong"},"birth":{},"baptism":{},"death":{},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"burial":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD4628","location_country":"United States","children_ids":["HD4648","HD4649"]}],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"FindAGrave","url":"https://www.findagrave.com"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"mary-caldwell"},"H02018":{"id":"H02018","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"bio":{"first_name":"Robert","middle_name":"Hunter","last_name":"Strong","married_names":[],"gender":"male","display_name":"Robert Hunter Strong"},"birth":{"year":1820,"month":8,"day":28,"city":"Rochester","county":"Monroe County","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1892,"month":5,"day":6,"city":"Waukesha","county":"Waukesha County","state":"Wisconsin","country":"United States"},"residence":{"city":"Milwaukee","county":"Milwaukee County","state":"Wisconsin","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM440","plot_notes":"Forest Home Cemetery Milwaukee WI per FA"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"generation_from_john_talcott":6,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"I00900","mother_id":"H00795"},"number_of_marriages":2,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00915","date_year":1845,"location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1857,"children_ids":["HD4625","HD4623","HD4624"]},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"I00916","date_year":1859,"location_country":"United States","children_ids":["HD4626","HD4627","HD4628","HD4629","HD4632","HD4633"]}],"education":[],"career":[{"role":"Clerk","organization":"Territorial Legislature of Wisconsin","start_year":1839,"end_year":1840,"notes":"Served during winter 1839-40."},{"role":"Businessman","organization":"Kellogg & Strong Steamboat Company and Warehouse, Milwaukee","notes":"Prominent Milwaukee merchant."},{"role":"Manager","organization":"Newberry Furnace Company"}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["wisconsin_migration"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Helped secure the land for Forest Home Cemetery","body":"Robert Hunter Strong was instrumental in securing the land for Forest Home Cemetery in Milwaukee and persuading St. Paul's Episcopal Church to establish the cemetery there — a civic contribution that anchored Milwaukee's most prominent burial ground. He came to Wisconsin around 1830, clerked in the territorial legislature in 1839-40, built his fortune through the Kellogg & Strong Steamboat company and Newberry Furnace, and was twice married."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Bridged two Strong-Hooker marriages and two frontier states","body":"Robert Hunter Strong was the son of the second Strong-Hooker marriage — Judge Elisha Beebe Strong and Dolly Goodwin Hooker — and the father of the man who would carry that name to a third generation: Beebe Hooker Strong, born Milwaukee 1866. He came to Wisconsin around 1830 at age ten, making the journey from the Rochester land grants his father had built to the Great Lakes frontier, and with him the Strong-Hooker legacy crossed into a new American West."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"Edward Hooker, Descendants of Rev. Thomas Hooker (1909)","url":"https://archive.org/details/descendantsofrev00hook"},{"label":"History of Descendants of Elder John Strong, Vol. 1 (1871)","url":"https://dn720908.ca.archive.org/0/items/historyofdescend0001dwig/historyofdescend0001dwig.pdf"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"robert-strong-1820"},"I00916":{"id":"I00916","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Rosa","middle_name":"Searls","last_name":"Strong","maiden_name":"Warner","married_names":["Strong"],"gender":"female","display_name":"Rosa Searls Strong"},"birth":{"year":1823,"month":11,"day":5,"city":"Springfield","county":"Hampden County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1911,"month":7,"day":14,"city":"Chicago","county":"Cook County","state":"Illinois","country":"United States"},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM440","plot_notes":"Forest Home Cemetery Milwaukee per 